### B. The Fall of Babylon to Cyrus — Named 150 Years Before His Birth

**The Prophecy (Characteristics Given):**

**Isaiah 44:28–45:4** (written c. 700 BC):

*"That saith of Cyrus, He is my shepherd, and shall perform all my pleasure: even saying to Jerusalem, Thou shalt be built; and to the temple, Thy foundation shall be laid. Thus saith the LORD to his anointed, to Cyrus, whose right hand I have holden, to subdue nations before him; and I will loose the loins of kings, to open before him the two leaved gates; and the gates shall not be shut."*

| Characteristic Given | Reference |
|---------------------|-----------|
| **Named by name: CYRUS** | Isa 44:28; 45:1 |
| He would be God's "shepherd" | Isa 44:28 |
| He would decree Jerusalem to be rebuilt | Isa 44:28 |
| He would decree the temple foundation laid | Isa 44:28 |
| Nations would be subdued before him | Isa 45:1 |
| "Two leaved gates" would open before him | Isa 45:1 |
| He would not know the LORD, yet be used by Him | Isa 45:4-5 |

**The Fulfillment (539 BC — 150+ years later):**

**Ezra 1:1-3** — *"Now in the first year of Cyrus king of Persia, that the word of the LORD by the mouth of Jeremiah might be fulfilled, the LORD stirred up the spirit of Cyrus king of Persia, that he made a proclamation throughout all his kingdom... Thus saith Cyrus king of Persia, The LORD God of heaven hath given me all the kingdoms of the earth; and he hath charged me to build him an house at Jerusalem."*

| Characteristic | Fulfillment |
|---------------|-------------|
| Named: Cyrus | **Cyrus the Great**, king of Persia |
| Subdued nations | Conquered the Medo-Persian Empire, then Babylon |
| Two-leaved gates | The gates of Babylon were left open the night Cyrus conquered it (Herodotus records this) |
| Decreed Jerusalem rebuilt | **Cyrus's decree** (Ezra 1:1-4) |
| Temple foundation | Jews returned and laid the foundation |
| Did not know the LORD | Cyrus was a pagan Persian, not a worshiper of YHWH |

**This is the only time God names a foreign ruler by name before his birth.**

